# Balanced Brackets

## Interviewer Prompt

Write a function that determines whether an input string has balanced brackets.

You are given an input string consisting of brackets——square `[ ]`, round `( )`, and curly `{ }`. The input string can include other text. Write a function that returns either `true` if the brackets in the input string are balanced or `false` if they are not. Balanced means that any opening bracket of a particular type must also have a closing bracket of the same type. Note that brackets cannot ‘overlap’ each other, e.g. `[(])`, and still be considered balanced.

An empty input string or a string without brackets can also be considered "balanced".

## Examples

    hasBalancedBrackets('[][(){}'); // false
    hasBalancedBrackets('({)}'); // false
    hasBalancedBrackets('({[]})'); // true
    hasBalancedBrackets('text ( is allowed ){rwwrwrrww [] ()}'); // true

## Interviewer Strategy Guide

  * Some interviewees may take the extra step of filtering out the non-bracket characters from the input string. Remember that this example `hasBalancedBrackets('({)}');` returns false, despite having two of each type of bracket.

## Solutions

In general an optimal approach is to keep a stack of open brackets, pushing as we come across them. As we come across closing brackets, if they match the most-recently-opened bracket we can pop the most-recently-opened bracket. If our stack is empty once we reach the end of the string, then our brackets must have been balanced.

Here's a solid solution (using RegEx to filter out all non-brackets):

    const bracketPattern = /[[\](){}]/g;
    const bracketPairs = { //keeps track of the possible bracket pairings
      '[' : ']',
      '(' : ')',
      '{' : '}'
    };
    function hasBalancedBrackets (inputString) {
      const inputBrackets = inputString.match(bracketPattern); // returns an array of all the brackets in the input
      const brackets = [];
      if (!inputString.length || !inputBrackets.length) {
        return true; // empty input string or no brackets in the string i.e. 'balanced' (throwing an error is fine also)
          opensStack.push(ch);
        } else if (closes.hasOwnProperty(ch)) {
          const mostRecentOpen = opensStack.pop();
          const correspondingClose = opens[mostRecentOpen];
          if (ch !== correspondingClose) return false;
        }
      }
      return opensStack.length === 0;
    }

Here is another similar solution:

    const openBrackets = {
        "{": true,
        "[": true,
        "(": true
    }

    const closeBrackets = {
        "}": "{",
        "]": "[",
        ")": "("
    }

    var isValid = function(s) {
        let stack = [];

        for (let i = 0; i < s.length; i++) {
            let char = s[i];
            if (openBrackets[char]) {
                stack.push(char);
            } else if (closeBrackets[char]) {
                if (stack[stack.length - 1] !== closeBrackets[char]) {
                    return false;
                } else {
                    stack.pop();
                }
            }
        }
        return !stack.length;
    };

## Time and Space Complexity

### Time Complexity: O(n)

  * For all solutions shown we have to loop through the input string once. If we take the step of filtering out non-brackets we loop through up to O(2n), however as constants cancel out this is still O(n).

### Space Complexity: O(n)

  * We store characters in the stack, which could potentially be the length of the entire string, e.g. `hasBalancedBrackets('(((((');`.

